ction in Denmark|2009]]'''\n| 474,041\n| 20.2 (#2)\n| {{Composition bar|3|13|hex=#25587E}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n|\n|-\n! '''[[2014 European Parliament election in Denmark|2014]]'''\n| 379,840\n| 17.7 (#3)\n| {{Composition bar|2|13|hex=#25587E}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n|\n|-\n! '''[[2019 European Parliament election in Denmark|2019]]'''\n| 648,203\n| 23.5 ('''#1''')\n| {{Composition bar|4|14|hex=#25587E}}\n| {{increase}} 2\n|\n|}\n\n==Youth and student wings==\n* [[Venstres Ungdom]]\n* [[Liberal Students of Denmark]] ''(Danmarks Liberale Studerende)''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liberalism]]\n* [[Contributions to liberal theory]]\n* [[Liberalism worldwide]]\n* [[List of liberal parties]]\n* [[Liberal democracy]]\n* [[Liberalism and radicalism in Denmark]]\n* [[Nordic agrarian parties]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references group=note />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tom Matz (2004), ''Venstre ved du hvor du har'' {{in lang|da}}. ForlagsKompagniet: N\u00f8rhaven Book.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Venstre (Denmark)}}\n* {{in lang|da}} [http://www.venstre.dk/ Venstre] official site\n* [http://www.venstre.dk/index.php?id=4620 Denmark's Liberal Party] presentation in English\n* {{in lang|da}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20071117065437/http://politiken.dk/ Party Profile from the newspaper Politiken]\n\n{{ELDR member parties}}\n{{Danish political parties}}\n{{Danish parliamentary election, 2007 navigation}}\n\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Conservative liberal parties]]\n[[Category:Nordic agrarian parties]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party member parties]]\n[[Category:1870 establishments in Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| colorcode = {{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Jakob Ellemann-Jensen]] \n| foundation = 1870, total reform in 1910\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Conservative liberalism]]<ref name=\"Kirchner1988\"/><ref name=\"Slomp2011\"/><ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{Cite web|url=http://parties-and-elections.eu/denmark.html|title=Denmark|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2019|website=Parties and Elections in Europe}}</ref><br />[[Agrarianism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"ErssonLane1998\">{{cite book\n|author1=Svante Ersson|author2=Jan-Erik Lane|title=Politics and Society in Western Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qw62oX96310C&pg=PA108|accessdate=17 August 2012|year=1998|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0-7619-5862-8|page=108}}</ref> ([[Nordic agrarian parties|Nordic]])<br />[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\"BengtssonHansen2013\"/>}}\n| headquarters = [[S\u00f8ller\u00f8d]]vej 30<br />2840 [[Holte]]\n| international = [[Liberal International]]\n| website = {{url|https://www.venstre.dk/}}\n| country = Denmark\n| name = Venstre, Denmark's Liberal Party\n| native_name = Venstre, Danmarks Liberale Parti\n| logo = Venstre Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| membership_year = 2016\n| membership = 35,957<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.dk/da/ofte-stillede-spoergsmaal/parti_hvor-mange-medlemmer-har-de-politiske-partier|title=Hvor mange medlemmer har de politiske partier?|website=Folketinget}}</ref>\n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref name=\"Colomer2008\">{{cite book|authorlink1=Josep Colomer|author=Josep M. Colomer|title=Political Institutions in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TZF8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA260|year=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-07354-2|page=260}}</ref>\n| european = [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]]\n| europarl = [[Renew Europe]]\n| affiliation1_title = Nordic affiliation\n| affiliation1 = [[Centre Group]]\n| youth_wing = [[Venstres Ungdom]]\n| wing1_title = Student wing\n| wing1 = [[Liberal Students of Denmark]]\n| colours = Blue\n| symbol = V\n| seats1_title = [[Folketing]]:\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|42|179|hex={{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]:\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|4|14|hex={{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Regions of Denmark|Regions]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistikbanken.dk/akva3|work=Statistics Denmark|title=AKVA3: Valg til regions r\u00e5d efter omr\u00e5de, parti og stemmer/kandidater/k\u00f8n|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|688|2444|hex={{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[List of municipalities of Denmark|Municipalities]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistikbanken.dk/valgk3|work=Statistics Denmark|title=VALGK3: Valg til kommunale r\u00e5d efter omr\u00e5de, parti og stemmer/kandidater/k\u00f8n|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|688|2432|hex={{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[Mayor]]s:\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|37|98|hex={{Venstre (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n}}\n'''Venstre'''<ref group=\"note\">The party name is officially not translated into any other language, but is in English often referred to as the Liberal Party. Similar rules apply for the name of the party's youth wing [[Venstres Ungdom]].</ref> ({{IPA-da|\u02c8v\u025bnst\u0281\u0250}}, literally \"left\"), full name '''Venstre, Danmarks Liberale Parti''' ({{lang-en|Left, Denmark's Liberal Party}}), is a [[conservative-liberal]],<ref name=\"Kirchner1988\">{{cite book|author1=Emil Joseph Kirchner|author2=Alistair H. Thomas|title=Liberal Parties in Western Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wtCIzAyQChQC&pg=PA280|accessdate=17 August 2012|year=1988|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-32394-9|page=280}}</ref><ref name=\"Slomp2011\">{{cite book|author=Hans Slomp|title=Europe, A Political Profile: An American Companion to European Politics: An American Companion to European Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LmfAPmwE6YYC|accessdate=17 August 2012|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39182-8|pages=415, 420}}</ref><ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/> [[Agrarianism|agrarian]]<ref name=\"KildalKuhnle2007\">{{cite book|author1=Nanna Kildal|author2=Stein Kuhnle|title=Normative Foundations of the Welfare State: The Nordic Experience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HFEX-6VzpGEC&pg=PA74|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-27283-9|page=74}}</ref> [[list of political parties in Denmark|political party in Denmark]]. Founded as part of a peasants' movement against the [[landed nobility|landed aristocracy]], today it espouses an [[economic liberalism|economically liberal]], pro\u2013[[free market]] ideology.<ref name=\"BengtssonHansen2013\">{{cite book|author1=\u00c5sa Bengtsson|author2=Kasper Hansen|author3=\u00d3lafur \u00de Har\u00f5arson |author4=Hanne Marthe Narud |author5=Henrik Oscarsson|title=The Nordic Voter: Myths of Exceptionalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJ4hAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA206|year=2013|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-1-907301-50-6|page=206}}</ref>\n\nVenstre is the [[major party]] of the [[centre-right]] in [[Denmark]], and the second-largest party in the country. The party has produced many [[List of Prime Ministers of Denmark|Prime Ministers]]. In the [[2019 Danish general election|2019 general elections]], Venstre received 23.4% of the vote and 43 out of 179 seats. Its current leader is [[Jakob Ellemann-Jensen]] following the resignation of [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] as chairman on 31 August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/indland/politik/art7360244/Lars-L%C3%B8kke-tr%C3%A6kker-sig-som-Venstres-formand|title=Lars L\u00f8kke tr\u00e6kker sig som Venstres formand|last=Kristiansen|first=Cecilie Lund|last2=Larsen|first2=Johan Blem|date=2019-08-31|website=Politiken|language=da-DK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\nThe party is a member of [[Liberal International]] and the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE) and has three MEPs in the [[European Parliament]].<ref name=\"Denmark-Results\">{{cite web | title=Europavalg | url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Temaer/2009/Europa/?v | publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] | accessdate=2009-06-07 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66bA0Wq8c?url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Temaer/2009/Europa/?v | archivedate=2012-04-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Ideology==\n{{Liberalism sidebar}}\nVenstre is categorised as [[centre-right]] on the [[political spectrum]].<ref name=\"Colomer2008\" /> It is a [[market liberalism|market liberal]] party<ref name=\"Almeida2012\">{{cite book|author=Dimitri Almeida|title=The Impact of European Integration on Political Parties: Beyond the Permissive Consensus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zGzZ0MpDjtsC&pg=PA98|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-69374-5|page=98\u2013}}</ref> within the [[Nordic agrarian parties|Nordic agrarian]] tradition,<ref name=\"almeida\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/depts/europe/conferences/tgsw/documents/TGSW_Almeida_Paper.pdf |title=Liberal Parties and European Integration |last=Almeida |first=Dimitri}}</ref> and today is notably more pro\u2013[[free market]] than its sister parties.<ref>{{cite book |title=Beyond Westminster and Congress: the Nordic experience |last=Esaiasson |first=Peter |author2=Heidar, Knut |authorlink2=Knut Heidar  |year=1999 |publisher=Ohio State University Press |location=Columbus |isbn=978-0-8142-0839-7 |page=377 }}</ref> Some describe it as classical liberal, since its leader from 1998 to 2009, [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]], is known for his authorship of the book ''[[From Social State to Minimal State]]''. His book advocated an extensive reform of the Danish [[welfare state]] along classical liberal lines, including lower taxes and less government interference in corporate and individual matters.\n\nSince the elections in 2001, Venstre has enacted a so-called \"tax stop\" in order to halt the growth in taxes seen during the previous eight years under the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]]. This tax stop has been under heavy fire from the parties on the [[left wing]] of Danish politics, allegedly for being \"asocial\" and \"only for the rich.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bt.dk/content/item/267451|title=Kritik af skattereform: De rige vinder og de fattige taber|date=24 February 2009|website=www.bt.dk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/indland/art4930974/AE-Skattestop-forgylder-de-rige|title=AE: Skattestop forgylder de rige|date=4 September 2002|website=Politiken}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Venstre1945.jpg|thumb|right|''Venstre'' 1945 election material ''(\"Venstre has been dealt a good hand\")'']]\n\n=== 1870\u20131910 ===\nVenstre was founded in 1870 under the name Det Forenede Venstre (\"The United Left\") and originally consisted of multiple conflicting groups, all united under the liberal ideology, the safeguarding of farmers' interests and opposition to the then conservative party [[H\u00f8jre]] (literally \"Right\"). After the party in 1872 gained an absolute majority in the [[Folketing]], it became the leading voice in the battle for [[parliamentarism]], whereafter the party in 1895 split in two, Venstrereformpartiet (\"Venstre Reform Party\") and Det Moderate Venstre (\"The Moderate Left\"). In 1905, social liberal factions split from the party and formed [[Radikale Venstre]] (also known as the Danish Social Liberal Party), and in 1910 Venstrereformpartiet and Det Moderate Venstre reunited again under the name Venstre.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/venstre/|title=Venstre|last=Bille|first=Lars|last2=R\u00fcdiger|first2=Mogens|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n=== 1910\u20132009 ===\nWith the decreasing numbers of farms and the growing urbanisation, membership and voter support dropped in the 1950s. During the 1960s the party gradually evolved from being a traditional farmers' party to a more general liberal party. In 1984 [[Uffe Ellemann-Jensen]] was elected chairman, and by profiling the liberal ideology in sharp confrontation to the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]], for example by campaigning for a reduction of the public sector, increasing market management and privatisation, and by being pro-EU, the party returned to its historical position as the biggest liberal party in the 1990s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter a disappointing [[1998 Danish general election|1998 general election]], Ellemann-Jensen resigned as chairman and [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] was elected in his place. He immediately changed the party's usual confrontational strategy, instead appealing to the political centre. In the [[2001 Danish general election|2001 general elections]] the party campaigned for tighter immigration policies and a \"tax stop\", which proved successful and the party once again became the biggest in parliament, winning 31.2% of the vote and 56 seats. Venstre formed a coalition government with the [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative People's Party]] and the [[Danish People's Party]]. For the first time since 1929 a liberal government was no longer dependent on the centre parties. Despite a small decline in both the [[2005 Danish general election|2005 general elections]] (29% and 52 seats) and the [[2007 Danish general election|2007 general elections]] (26.2% and 46 seats), the party remained the biggest and the coalition government continued.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 5 April 2009 Fogh Rasmussen resigned as chairman, instead serving as [[Secretary General of NATO]]. In his place [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] was elected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/indland/politik/art4795728/Anders-Fogh-er-tr%C3%A5dt-tilbage|title=Anders Fogh er tr\u00e5dt tilbage|last=Lund|first=Kenneth|date=2009-04-05|website=Politiken|language=da-DK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009\u2013present ===\nIn the [[2011 Danish general election|2011 general elections]] the gained 26.7% of the vote and 47 seats, but wasn't able to form a government, instead leading the opposition of Prime Minister [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]'s Social Democratic coalition.\n\nEven though the party lost voter support in the [[2015 Danish general election|2015 general elections]], only gaining 19.5% of the vote, the party formed a minority government. This government was short lived, and in 2016 L\u00f8kke Rasmussen invited the Conservative People's Party and the [[Liberal Alliance (Denmark)|Liberal Alliance]] to form a coalition government instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Samfund,_jura_og_politik/Samfund/Danske_politiske_partier_og_bev\u00e6gelser/Venstre|title=Venstre {{!}} Gyldendal - Den Store Danske|last=Bille|first=Lars|last2=Bille|first2=Mogens|date=2009-02-02|website=denstoredanske.dk|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign of the [[2019 Danish general election|2019 general elections]] L\u00f8kke Rasmussen published an autobiography, in which he opened up for the possibility of forming a government with the Social Democrats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/folketingsvalg/loekke-aabner-sv-regering-efter-valget|title=L\u00f8kke \u00e5bner for SV-regering efter valget|website=DR|language=da-DK|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref> This was seen as controversial in the liberal \"blue bloc\", and Social Democratic leader [[Mette Frederiksen]] immediately declined the proposition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/folketingsvalg/mette-frederiksen-afviser-loekke-sv-regering-kan-ikke-komme-paa-tale|title=Mette Frederiksen afviser L\u00f8kke: SV-regering kan ikke komme p\u00e5 tale|website=DR|language=da-DK|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing internal fighting in the party, L\u00f8kke Rasmussen and vice chairman [[Kristian Jensen]] both resigned on 31 August 2019. On 21 September 2019 political spokesman and former Minister for Environment and Food [[Jakob Ellemann-Jensen]] was elected the party's next chairman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/indland/politik/art7399808/Jakob-Ellemann-Jensen-er-valgt-som-Venstres-nye-formand|title=Jakob Ellemann-Jensen er valgt som Venstres nye formand|date=2019-09-21|website=Politiken|language=da-DK|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>\n\n===Prime Ministers===\n* [[Johan Henrik Deuntzer]] (July 24, 1901{{snd}}January 14, 1905)\n* [[Jens Christian Christensen]] (January 14, 1905{{snd}}October 12, 1908)\n* [[Niels Neergaard]] (October 12, 1908{{snd}}August 16, 1909)\n* [[Ludvig Holstein-Ledreborg]] (August 16, 1909{{snd}}October 28, 1909)\n* [[Klaus Berntsen]] (July 5, 1910{{snd}}June 21, 1913)\n* [[Niels Neergaard]] (May 5, 1920{{snd}}April 23, 1924)\n* [[Thomas Madsen-Mygdal]] (December 14, 1926{{snd}}April 30, 1929)\n* [[Knud Kristensen]] (November 7, 1945{{snd}}November 13, 1947)\n* [[Erik Eriksen]] (October 30, 1950{{snd}}September 30, 1953)\n* [[Poul Hartling]] (December 19, 1973{{snd}}February 13, 1975)\n* [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] (November 27, 2001{{snd}}April 5, 2009)\n* [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] (April 5, 2009{{snd}}October 3, 2011; June 28, 2015{{snd}}June 27, 2019)\n\n===Leaders since 1929===\n{{Officeholder table start\n| showorder          = y\n| showimage          = y\n| image_title        = Portrait\n| officeholder_title = Leader\n| showtermstart      = y\n| showtermend        = y\n| showparty          = n\n| showtermlenght     = y\n| showdefencebranch  = n\n}}\n{{Officeholder table\n| order             = 1\n| image             = MadsenMygdal.jpg |bSize = 85px\n| officeholder      = [[Thomas Madsen-Mygdal]]\n| officeholder_sort = Madsen, Thomas\n| born_year         = 1876\n| died_year         = 1943\n| term_start        = 1929\n| term_end          = 1941\n| timeinoffice      = {{age in years|1929|1941}} years\n}}\n{{Officeholder table\n| order             = 2\n|